***Hello Guys.....***
	This particular problem can be solved using O(N) complexity. To be more accurate, we need run time of O(2N) where N is the length of the array. Firstly, we need to calculate the ***total sum*** of the array. We need a long variable since the sum could be large.
		Secondly we iterrate over the array once again and add each number to the **leftSum**. We find the **rightSum** using the **leftSum** and **totalSum**. Here is the java solution for the problem using the above approach.
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumAverageDifference(int[] nums) {
        long sum=0,leftSum=0;
        int leftCount=1,rightCount=nums.length - 1;
        for (int i=0;i<nums.length;i++)
            sum+=nums[i];
        long lhs,rhs,min=999999999999999l;
        int index=0;
        for (int i=0;i<nums.length;i++)
        {
            leftSum+=nums[i];
            lhs=leftSum/leftCount;
            rhs=(rightCount>0)?(sum-leftSum)/rightCount:0;
            long avgDiff=((lhs-rhs)>0?lhs-rhs:rhs-lhs);
            if (i==0){min=avgDiff;}
            if (avgDiff<min)
            {
                min=avgDiff;
                index=i;
            }
            leftCount++;
            rightCount--;
         }
         return index;       
    }
}
```

