# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- First calculate total sum of array.
- Use the total sum to calculate suffix sum.
- Maintain prefix sum while calculating min average.
- Use long to store sums to avoid Integer Overflow.
# Complexity
- Time complexity  :  O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
- Space complexity : O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumAverageDifference(int[] nums) {
        long sumTotal = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++){
            sumTotal += nums[i];
        }

        long sumPre = 0;
        long suf_avg = 0;
        long min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        int ans = -1;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
            ///Calculating Prefix Sum.
            sumPre += nums[i];
            long pre_avg = Math.abs(sumPre/(i+1)); 

            //For last index the suffix average will be zero
            if(i == nums.length-1){
                suf_avg = 0;
            }
            else{
                suf_avg = Math.abs((sumTotal - sumPre)/(nums.length - i - 1));
            }

            //System.out.println(" pre : " + pre_avg + " suf : " + suf_avg);
            long avg = Math.abs(pre_avg - suf_avg);

            // Minimum possible difference is zero. So, returning index.
            if(avg == 0) return i;
            if(min > avg){
                min = avg;
                ans = i;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

